renc Tóth investigates how older transatlantic images of American Indians influenced the alliance between Native activists and Central European groups, how this coalition developed and functioned, and how the US government and the regimes of the Eastern Bloc responded to this transatlantic alliance. This book not only places the American Indian radical sovereignty movement in an international context, but also recasts it as a transnational struggle, thus connecting domestic US social and political history to the history of Cold War transatlantic relations and global movements.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAnti-imperialist movementsxHistoryy20th century. 0aIndians of North AmericaxCivil rightsxHistoryy20th century. 0aIndians of North AmericaxGovernment relationsxHistoryy20th century. 0aIndians of North AmericaxPolitics and governmenty20th century. 0aSovereigntyxHistoryy20th century. 4aAmerican Studies : Indigenous Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2016z978311149098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438461236423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438461236/original  a978-3-11-149098-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles